      "CIA TORTURE TAPES: In November 2005, CIA officer Jose Rodriguez ordered the destruction of 92 videotapes documenting the waterboarding and interrogation of CIA detainees. The tapes were destroyed despite explicit court orders to preserve evidence and congressional requests for documents. A special prosecutor investigated and concluded no charges were warranted. The tapes reportedly showed treatment even more brutal than the CIA had described to Congress.",
      "ENRON AND ARTHUR ANDERSEN: In response to an SEC investigation, Arthur Andersen employees shredded thousands of documents and deleted electronic files related to the Enron audit. Partners at the firm directed staff to destroy materials under the firm's routine document retention policy; which was invoked specifically to conceal evidence. The firm was convicted of obstruction of justice in 2002; though the conviction was later overturned by the Supreme Court on narrow grounds.",
      "SECRET SERVICE JANUARY 6 TEXTS: The Secret Service deleted text messages from January 5 and January 6, 2021; after the Department of Homeland Security Inspector General requested them be preserved. The messages were erased during a planned device migration. The January 6 Select Committee subpoenaed the messages. The Secret Service claimed most could not be recovered. The DHS IG referred the matter to the DOJ; no charges were filed.",
      "IRAN-CONTRA SHREDDING: Oliver North and Fawn Hall shredded thousands of documents related to the Iran-Contra affair in November 1986, just as investigators were closing in. North testified that he shredded documents to protect the operation and the individuals involved. Despite the destruction, enough evidence survived to document the illegal arms sales and fund diversion; but many details were permanently lost.",
      "WATERGATE TAPES GAP: The 18.5-minute gap in a key Watergate tape recording of a conversation between President Nixon and chief of staff H.R. Haldeman has never been explained. Rose Mary Woods, Nixon's secretary, claimed she accidentally erased part of the tape; a demonstration of her explanation was widely ridiculed. Forensic analysis concluded the erasure was deliberate and involved at least five separate operations.",
